%%example 2
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3S65 H65 DK987 C87654,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|What to do After a Double|ah|Example 2|mb|1nd?|lb|*bPlease make a bid for South.^^r|NT|^B@2
In this case, I recommend you redouble, showing a single suited hand. With a very weak hand, you are better playing in the weak hand's long suit.|mb|R|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT|| 

%%example 3
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3SK9 HJ9 DKQ65 C87654,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|What to do After a Double|ah|Example 3|mb|1nd?|lb|*bPlease make a bid for South.^^P|NT|^B@2
You should consider passing with this hand, With 9 points, you are willing to play 1N doubled.|MB|P|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


NT||

%%example 4
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3SA987 HQ987 D65 C987,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|What to do After a Double|ah|Example 4|mb|1nd?|lb|*bPlease make a bid for South.^^2H|NT|^B@2
Bid 2@H, showing hearts and spades. As mentioned above, you can be 4-4 and show 2 suits. If you play the new DONT, redouble and bid 2@H over 2@C.|MB|2h|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||


%%example 5
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3SKQJ987 HA65 D987 C9,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|What to do After a Double|ah|Example 5|mb|1nd?|lb|*bPlease make a bid for South.^^4H|NT|^B@2
Bid 4@H (transfer) if you play Texas, or 4@S if you don't. This is the same as what you would have done with no double. There is no point in letting the opponents find out if they can compete.|MB|4H|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


 


%%example 6
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3SKQJ65 HA65 DQ65 C65,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|What to do After a Double|ah|Example 6|mb|1nd?|lb|*bPlease make a bid for South.^^3S|NT|^B@2
Bid 3@S (natural and forcing). This gives partner a choice of games. At first blush, you may feel that not being able to transfer is a problem, However, the advantage of a transfer over a strong NT (hiding the strong hand) does not really apply over a weak NT, since both hands are the same strength.|MB|3S|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


