Bid 2N, and pass partner's forced 3@C response.|MB|2np3cppp|
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


NT||

%%example D
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3s98 h987 dKQJ98 cQ98,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|What to do After an Overcall|ah|Example D|mb|1n2h?|
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


lb|*bPlease make a bid for South.^^2n|NT|^B@2
Bid 2N. Over partner's forced 3@C, bid 3@D, indicating that you wish to play in 3@D. Partner must pass.|mb|2np3cp3d|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


NT||

%%example E
st||pn|You,,Partner,|md|3sKQJ98 hA98 d987 c98,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|What to do After an Overcall|ah|Example E|mb|1n2h?|
pg| ***** 49 ***** |


lb|*bPlease make a bid for South.^^2n|NT|^B@2
Bid 2N. Over partner's forced 3@C, bid 3@S, indicating a hand with spades and game invitational values.|mb|2np3cp3s|
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


NT|^B@2 Note that if you play my alternative treatment, where that sequence shows game forcing values with a heart stopper, you have to make a decision. Playing match points I would just bid 2@S to play. Playing IMPs I would treat this as a game forcing hand and bid 2N followed by 3@S.|
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


NT||

